      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks for catching that. i see the delete now. but is there a better way to handle this besides just adding a delete? like, in a big production system, manually managing every single pointer like this feels kinda risky. if we miss one more, the whole server might crash. is there a standard practice to make sure this doesn't happen again?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "In production systems, safe and automatic memory management is crucial to preventing leaks and crashes. The recommended approach in C++ is to use smart pointers, which are higher-level abstractions provided by the standard library with automatic memory management features. Among smart pointers, `std::unique_ptr` is a commonly used choice for exclusive ownership semantics.\n\n`std::unique_ptr` is a smart pointer that owns and manages another object through a pointer and disposes of that object when the `std::unique_ptr` goes out of scope. Switch to `std::unique_ptr` to avoid manually writing `delete`, and it will automatically release memory when it's no longer needed. Here's how the corrected code example would look:\n\n```cpp\n#include <iostream>\n#include <memory> // Include for smart pointers\n\nstd::unique_ptr<double> processTransaction(int i) {\n    auto txAmount = std::make_unique<double>(100.0 + i); // Use make_unique for simplicity\n    // Simulating some processing\n    std::cout << \"Processing transaction \" << i << \": \" << *txAmount << std::endl;\n    \n    // No need to 'delete' as unique_ptr takes care of that\n    double result = (*txAmount) *",
